params.basePricePNS: CAREFUL! This is the base price for prices in the perpetual contract's                     order book. The order book is able to represent 2^24-1 price levels. The                     base price determines the minimum price the order book can represent in                     Price Number System (PNS).                     For example, if the PNS for the perpetual is configured with 2 decimals and                     the lowest price the order book can represent is desired to be $1000.01,                     then basePricePNS should be set to 1_000_00, the last two digits accounting                     for the two decimal places, the value being .01 less because the price                     levels DO NOT INCLUDE the basePricePNS.
params.initMarginFracHdths: is the Initial Margin Fraction (IMF) in hundredths. It is                            constrained to the range [1, 10,000], which corresponds to an IMF                            range of [1/100, 100.00]. IMF is synonymous with the leverage of a                            position. This value determines the maximum initial leverage a                            position may be opened with. This value is derated towards unity and                            eventually 1/100th as open interest of the perpetual contract                            increases towards the maximum open interest.
params.lotDecimals: CAREFUL! This is the number of decimals to use for the perpetual contract's                    position lot size, the Lot Number System (LNS). LNS is limited to 40-bits                    and the maximum lot size of a position is thus 2^40 - 1, divided by                    10^lotDecimals. This directly effects the maximum notional open interest                    possible for the perpetual contract as well as the minimum amount that can                    be traded (ignoring the minimum post and settle amounts). This value is                    constrained to the absolute range [0,6], but jointly constrained with the                    priceDecimals value to sum to 6 or less, both values being greater than or                    equal to zero.
params.maintMarginFracHdths: is the Maintenance Margin Fraction (MMF) in hundredths. It is                             constrained to the range [1, 10,000], which corresponds to an MMF                             range of [1/100, 100.00]. The MMF determines when a position can be                             liquidated and is used to compute the value a position must exceed                             to avoid liquidation. It must exceed initMarginFracHdths.                             IMPORTANT: See dev note warning below about maintMarginFracHdths.
params.makerFeePer100K: is the maker fee in hundred-thousandths. It is constrained to the                        absolute range [0, _MAX_FEE].
params.name: is the name of the perpetual contract, limited to _MAX_NAME_BYTES.
params.perpId: is the unique id for this perpetual contract. Cannot already be in use; previous               contract must be properly unwound and deleted from the exchange before               re-assigning. Valid values in the range [0,_MAX_CONTRACT_ID].
params.priceDecimals: CAREFUL! This is the number of decimals to use for the order book's Price                      Number System (PNS). It directly determines the range of prices that the                      order book can operate and the minimum spread. It is constrained to the                      absolute range [0,6], but jointly constrained with the lotDecimals value                      to sum to 6 or less, both values being greater than or equal to zero.                      For example, there are only 2^24 - 2 price levels, ~16M. If two price                      decimals are specified and the basePricePNS is zero, then the approximate                      price range of the order book would be [$0.01, $((2^24 - 2)/100)] The                      spread resolution would be in increments of $0.01. The perpetual would not                      be able to trade at prices above $((2^24 - 2)/100).
params.symbol: is the symbol for the perpetual contract, limited to _MAX_SYMBOL_BYTES.
params.takerFeePer100K: is the taker fee in hundred-thousandths. It is constrained to the                        absolute range [0, _MAX_FEE].

decreasePositionCollateral(uint256,uint2.details: IMPORTANT: If function reverts, protocol supporting infrastructure should attempt to                 correct invalidly specified arguments in a subsequent re-try.CAREFUL: The behavior is not symmetric for long and short positions because the borrowing               margin requirement (BMR) is calculated at the current mark price. This means that               a position that starts with a $10k deposit and gains delta PNL of $10k, will have               a different BMR if it is long than if it is short.               A concrete example of this are long and short positions entered at $100k with               $10k deposited. If the impact adjusted price is set to the mark price for               convenience, then if both position holders wished to remove $10k from the               position, then the new positions formed for a borrowing margin fraction of 10               (1000 in hundredths) would have the following properties: markPNS=$111,111.2 markPNS=$90909.0               Note that the Short position's FMV is now lower than the long position's, despite               both removing $10k. If it is desired to have short position's maintain higher               fmv, it is recommended to reduce the BMF value accordingly for short positions.

params.borrowMarginFracHdths: is the borrowing margin fraction in hundredths. This is the                              leverage permitted of the reduced collateral position at the                              current mark price. The initMarginFracHdths is not used here                              because market conditions may dictate a more conservative                              collateral requirement, which this parameter facilitates.                              This parameter is superceded by the dynamic system initial margin                              fraction if it implies lower leverage.                              Acceptable range is [1, perp.initMarginFracHdths].                              See CAREFUL dev note.
params.impactAdjPricePNS: is the impact adjusted price used to compute the PNL of the position                          where collateral is being decreased. This should be an impact price of                          the position or adjusted impact price (if the position moves or sweeps                          the order book--adjustment should be compensated by reducing the                          borrowMarginFracHdths to limit risk and reduce the amount of                          collateral that can be decreased from the position).

returns.leaves: is an ordered array of 256-bit containers that represent the leaves of the                16-bit order id index.                The Least-Significant Bit (LSB) of the first element of the array is order id                zero, which is reserved as _NULL_ORDER_ID. It is not used for orders.                The second bit of the first element of the array is order id 1 and so forth.                Except for order id zero, if the value of a bit is one, it indicates that the                order id is in use for an existing order. If the value of the bit is zero, it                indicates the order id is not currently in use. For order id zero, the bit will                be one to indicate the reserved status.                The LSB of the second element of the array is order id 256, the LSB of the third                element of the array is order id 512, and so so forth up to the last possible                order id, which is the Most-Significant Bit (MSB) of the last element of the                array, order id 65535.
returns.numOrders: is the number of order ids currently in use in the returned order id index                   leaves.
returns.root: is a 256-bit container with each bit corresponding to a leaf in the leaves. The              Least-Significant Bit (LSB) corresponds to the first leaves element, and so forth.              If a bit is zero it indicates that all ids in the corresponding leaf node are in              use. If the bit is one, it indicates that one or more numbers in the corresponding              leaf node is NOT in use.

unwindContractByOwner(uint256,uint256,bo.details: The unwind process is a three-stage process as follows:     Stage 1: Freeze       1. The perpetual contract is paused.       2. Backend infrastructure assesses the recorded mark price in the perpetual contract,          potentially updating it through a governance process that may involve decoupling from          the price oracle.       3. Backend infrastructure calls Owner::prepareUnwindContract to freeze all operations that          would change position Fair Market Values (FMVs). This includes:            - Mark price updates            - Funding updates            - Liquidations            - ADL            - Force closes            - Position collateral modifications          This ensures FMVs remain stable for calculation in stage 2.     [Optional]: Set An Appropriate Mark Price For The Unwind Event       4  Backend infrastructure determines an appropriate mark price for the unwind process,          which is then set using Owner::updateMarkPricePNSByOwner().          See documentation for that function.     Stage 2: Commit FMV Sum       5. Backend infrastructure computes the sum of the Fair Market Value (FMV) at the recorded          mark price for all positions where FMV > 0. The frozen state ensures this sum remains          valid.       6. Backend infrastructure adjusts the perpetual contract's insurance balance, if necessary,          with an internal transfer (either to or from the perpetual contract's insurance balance).       7. Backend infrastructure calls Owner::initUnwindContract to commit the calculated FMV sum          to the perpetual state.     [Optional]: Trigger Unwind       8. Owner::triggerUnwindContract may be called to emit an event if Stages 1 & 2          have been completed. Backend infrastructure with PositionAdministrator privileges          monitors for this event and upon receipt, performs the unwindContract operation.          Communicating with the PositionAdministrator services through the blockchain enables          isolation from other communication methods, reducing attack surface.     Stage 3: Execute Unwind       9. Owner::unwindContractByOwner or PositionAdministrator::unwindContract is called          repeatedly until all positions are unwound.IMPORTANT - CAREFUL: Once Stage 1 is initiated, FMV-modifying operations are blocked                           until the unwind process is complete. The freeze remains in place                           through Steps 2 and 3.IMPORTANT - CAREFUL: Cannot unpause the contract once `prepareUnwindContract` has been called,                           until the unwind process is complete and the contract is removed or                           the preparation is cleared via `clearPrepareUnwindContract()` (only                           possible before Stage 2).IMPORTANT: If the perpetual insurance and position balance are zero at the start of this                 process, positions will be unwound without payment. This is not handled                 through the "allowWithoutPayment" parameter and does not emit                 PositionUnwoundWithoutPayment events. However, it is possible in this                 situation to see the position's FMV at unwind in the PositionUnwound event and                 for the protocol to consider compensation through an internal transfer at a                 later time.

params.allowWithoutPayment: is a boolean that when true, instructs the function to unwind                            positions, clearing them from the perpetual, even if the calculated                            payment to the position holder cannot be paid. A                            PositionUnwoundWithoutPayment event is emitted that contains the                            unpaid amount. This allows clearing of state if the perpetual is                            insolvent.
params.maxPosToUnwind: is the maximum number of positions to unwind per call to unwind. If set                       to zero then this function will initialize the unwind balance and mark                       the unwind process as having started. See dev notes below for                       implications. CAREFUL!

Buy to liquidate or purchase liquidations differ from liquidations to                         the book as follows:                           - Depending on the perpetual contract configuration, the may be                             permissionless. (See Information::getLiquidationInfo for more                             details).                           - They are performed at the current mark price.                           - The mark price must be at or beneath the purchase liquidation                             price for long orders (at or above it for short orders). The                             purchase liquidation price is a price between the positions                             liquidation price and bankruptcy price. (See documentation for                             CalculationsLib::getLiquidationPurchasePrice for more details).                           - The proceeds from the liquidation are distributed using different                             ratios than permissioned liquidations to the order book. See                             documentation for Perpetual::btl*Per100K and                             Information::getLiquidationInfo for additional information.                           - An distribution of liquidation proceeds to the liquidation                             purchaser is possible, depending on the value of                             Perpetual::btlBuyerAmtPer100K. This distribution is made to the                             acquired position's settled deposit amount.

cancelDecreaseCollateralRequest(uint256).notice: Cancels the user's pending decrease collateral request. Can be called by the user         to cancel a pending request before the backend processes it.

clearInitUnwindContract(uint256).notice: Clears the perpetual contract unwind process initialization state if the unwind process         has not yet started.

clearPrepareUnwindContract(uint256).notice: Clears the unwind preparation if the unwind process has not yet been initialized.         This allows backing out of the preparation stage if needed before committing the FMV sum.

createAccount(uint256).notice: createAccount creates a user account on the exchange for the msg.sender address, if                       such an account doesn't already exist and sufficient collateral token is                       being deposited.

declineDecreaseCollateralRequest(uint256.notice: Clears a user's decrease collateral request. Called by position administrator to         decline a pending request after risk evaluation.

decreasePositionCollateral(uint256,uint2.notice: Decreases the collateral of an existing position in the specified perpetual contract if         a request to decrease collateral has been previously submitted.         IMPORTANT: This is part of a two-step process described in the documentation for                    Operations::requestDecreasePositionCollateral         A successful request to decrease collateral results in the account mapping         decCollateralRequestMap being populated with expiryTS, amountCNS and clampToMaximum for the         specified perpetual contract.         This function reverts if the calling account is frozen, the perp contract is paused or there         is no request found for the account and the specified perpetual contract.         This function emits on failure and clears the decrease collateral request (requiring         another request to the protocol) if:           - The decrease collateral parameters are expired.           - The corresponding position no longer exists.           - The amount specified, amountCNS, exceeds the maximum withdrawable amount and             clampToMaximum is set to false.           - The impact adjusted price exceeds the current reference price for a long position             (or is less than it for a short position).         Reverts on failure but DOES NOT clear decrease collateral parameters if the reference price is stale.

depositCollateral(uint256).notice: depositCollateral allows an existing exchange account to deposit additional exchange                           collateral tokens into their account from an external wallet. The                           exchange account id is looked up through the msg.sender address                           within the exchange's map of addresses to account ids.

depositToProtocol(uint256).notice: depositToProtocol allows the owner account to transfer collateral tokens from an                           external wallet to the protocol balance.

execFwdPositionOps((uint256,uint256,(uin.notice: execFwdPositionOps executes forwarded position operations from an address with         Administrator role privileges on behalf of user accounts who have approved forwarding         by such a role. The forwarded operations include standard order book order types, such         as Open Long etc. as well as the ability to increase a position's collateral.

execFznAccountPosOps((uint256,(uint256,u.notice: execFznAccountPosOps executes frozen account position operations, specifically orders                              to close the positions of frozen accounts.

execOrder((uint256,uint256,uint8,uint256.notice: Executes an account's order, as described in the order description, orderDesc. If the         resulting executed order posts to a perpetual's order book, the signature value         returned uniquely identifies the order. Otherwise, a signature with all values set to         zero is returned.

execOrders((uint256,uint256,uint8,uint25.notice: Executes zero or more operations and orders as specified by an account in the array of         operation descriptions, operations, and order descriptions, orderDescs. Operations are         limited to perpetual contract oracle updates. Available orders are presented in the         documentation for struct OrderDesc. Well formed operation and order descriptions will         be executed and in the event of recoverable errors, will emit error messages if         revertOnFail is false. Irrecoverable errors will result in the transaction being         reverted. The returned array, signatures, are the uniquely identifiying order         signatures corresponding to each individual order description in the event that its         execution results in a post to the perpetual contract's order book.         IMPORTANT: This will emit OracleDisabled event and continue after executing oracle                    update operations if the perpetual contract that is the target of the                    update is configured to ignore oracle prices (see Perpetual::ignOracle and                    Owner::setIgnOracle).

execPerpOps((uint256,uint256,uint8,uint3.notice: execPerpOps executes a batch of perpetual operations as described in OpDescEnum (see                     documentation for that enum).

forceClose(uint256,uint256,uint256[],boo.notice: Force closes the position of a specified account id within a perpetual contract by         deleveraging the position against the specified, opposing, positions. The deleveraging         is performed at the current mark price.

forceResetWithdrawRateLimit().notice: Helper to clear the current withdraw limit interval.         Intended for use after freezing abusive accounts to unblock withdrawals.

getFundingSumAtBlock(uint256,uint256).notice: Gets the funding sum of a perpetual contract from the funding event block prior to the         specified block number.

getLiquidationInfo(uint256).notice: gets the liquidation parameters for the specified perpetual contract.

getMarginFractions(uint256,uint256).notice: getMarginFractions returns the perpetual's initial, maintenance and current dynamic                            initial margin fraction in hundredths.

getNextPriceAboveWithOrders(uint256,uint.notice: Gets the next price above (more than) the specified price that contains orders.

getNextPriceBelowWithOrders(uint256,uint.notice: Gets the next price below (less than) the specified price that contains orders.

getOrderIdIndex(uint256).notice: Fetches the order id index data of the specified perpetual's order id index to allow         the caller to determine all currently used and unused order ids in the 16-bit order         space.

getOrdersAtPriceLevel(uint256,uint256,ui.notice: Gets a page of orders at the specified price level.

getPerpetualInfo(uint256).notice: gets a subset of the properties of the specified perpetual contract.

getPosition(uint256,uint256).notice: Gets the position of the specified account in the specified perpetual contract. If the         position does not exist, all values of positionInfo will be zero.

getPositions(uint256,uint256,uint256).notice: Gets a page of positions within the specified perpetual contract.

getUnwindInfo(uint256).notice: Gets information about a perpetual contract's unwind state.

getVolumeAtBookPrice(uint256,uint256).notice: Returns the volume of orders at a given price level on the order book.

increasePositionCollateral(uint256,uint2.notice: Increases an account's collateral in an existing position.

initUnwindContract(uint256,uint256).notice: Initializes the unwind process by committing the sum of positive FMVs. This is the Stage 2         of a three-stage unwind process. The perpetual must be frozen first via `prepareUnwindContract()`.         Once initialized, Stage 3 (`unwindContract`) can begin.

initialize(address).notice: initialize  initializes the Exchange on-chain. After called, the                     address msg.sender becomes the Owner role of the exchange. Transfer of                     ownership is a two-step process (see OpenZeppelin Ownable2Step                     documentation).

liquidation((uint256,uint256,uint256,boo.notice: liquidation performs liquidation of the specified position if the value of the position                     is underneath the maintenance margin. The maintenance margin is used to                     determine a liquidation price for the position. If the liquidation price                     is beneath the perpetual contract's mark price for a long position (or                     above it for a short position), the position can be liquidated.                     Liquidation is performed by selling the position to the order book. If the                     fill price of this operation is at the bankruptcy price or below (when the                     margin of the position is valued at zero), then liquidation will revert (it                     must revert because matching changes state).                     The proceeds of a liquidation are divided between the original position                     holder, the protocol, and the perpetual insurance fund, according to the                     values of the following perpetual parameters:                          - Perpetual::liqUserAmtPer100K                          - Perpetual::liqInsAmtPer100K                     See the documentation of these values in the Perpetual struct.                     Optionally, the liquidation function facilitates partial liquidation,                     wherein part of a position is liquidated and the proceeds are directed to                     the remaining portion of the position as collateral to place it above the                     maintenance margin.

liquidations((uint256,uint256,uint256,bo.notice: liquidations attempts to perform a batch of operations, emitting events if possible                      when errors are encountered if revertOnFail is false. Liquidation matches                      against the book and if the resulting fill price places the liquidated                      position beneath the bankruptcy price, the liquidation must revert, which                      would then cause any batch with such a liquidation to also revert.

pauseContract(uint256).notice: pauseContract pauses the specified perpetual contract, which blocks new orders and                       position operations except for order cancellation and increasing position                       collateral. See important dev notes below.

prepareUnwindContract(uint256).notice: Freezes all operations that modify position fair market values (FMVs) for the specified         perpetual contract. This is the Stage 1 of a three-stage unwind process. Once frozen, no mark         price updates, funding updates, liquidations, ADL, force closes, or         collateral modifications are allowed. This ensures FMVs remain stable while backend         calculates the sum of positive FMVs.

removeContract(uint256).notice: removeContract removes a perpetual contract from the exchange.

requestDecreasePositionCollateral(uint25.notice: Requests the ability to decrease position collateral for the calling account in the         specified perpetual contract. This stores the user's request which will be executed         by the position admin after risk evaluation.         This is part of a two-step process:           1. User calls Operations::requestDecreasePositionCollateral to request a position              collateral decrease.           2. Protocol detects event log CollateralDecreaseRequested, evaluates risk and              either:                a. Calls PositionAdmin::decreasePositionCollateral to perform the decrease.                b. Calls PositionAdmin::declineDecreaseCollateralRequest to decline the request.

setAddressBlockStatus(address[],bool).notice: Sets the block status for one or more addresses. Blocked addresses cannot         create accounts regardless of whitelist status.

setAddressWhitelisted(address[],bool).notice: Sets the whitelist status for one or more addresses. When whitelisting is enabled,         only whitelisted addresses can create accounts (unless they are blocked).

setAdministrator(address,bool).notice: setAdministrator CAREFUL! This function allows an address to be permitted to the role                          of administrator. An administrator (not to be confused with a price                          administrator, which is a different role) can do important,                          financially impactful operations on a perpetual contract including                          pausing a contract, permissioned order cancellation, freezing of                          accounts, and order forwarding.                          This role is not suitable for a multi-sig because the frequency of                          operations and number of operations is too high. Protection against                          this role being co-opted comes in the form of the price oracle                          guarding operations to be within acceptable tolerance, forwarding only                          to users who have granted such permission (and never to transfers on                          or off exchange from a user wallet). A last resort is the owner called                          halt function which blocks addresses with this role from acting on the                          exchange.                          The number of administrators is not limited as this role will likely                          operate with both failover and geographic redundancy.

setBuyToLiquidateBuyerRestriction(uint25.notice: Sets the buy to liquidate buyer restriction option. This option makes the buy to         liquidate functionality permissioned when restrictBuyers is true. Permissionless         otherwise.         To disable the buy to liquidate feature altogether, set restrictBuyers to true and         clear all specified buyers from the State::_liquidationBuyers mapping.

setBuyToLiquidateParams(uint256,uint256,.notice: Sets the buy to liquidate split for the proceeds of a liquidation, directing         configurable portions of the funds to the insurance fund, the original position holder,         the position buyer (liquidator), and the protocol.

setContractPaused(uint256,bool).notice: setContractPaused pauses or unpauses the specified perpetual contract, which blocks new                           orders and position operations except for order cancellation and                           increasing position collateral.

setDcpBorrowThreshold(uint256,uint256).notice: setDcpBorrowThreshold sets the threshold at which decreasePositionCollateral                              operations revert due to high open interest. When the OI                              reaches or exceeds this threshold DCP operations will                              revert to reduce risk during high OI conditions.

setExchangeHalted(bool).notice: setExchangeHalted CAREFUL! This function halts the entire exchange making all external                           functions except those restricted to the Owner role blocked from all                           users (including the Owner role).

setFeeParams(uint256,uint256).notice: setFeeParams sets the fee split between the insurance and protocol for fees collected         on maker and taker orders that open a position. (See documentation on setMakerFee and         setTakerFee).

setFreezeStatus(address,uint8).notice: setFreezeStatus sets the frozen status of an account to any of the values documented                         in FreezeStatusEnum.

setFrozen(address,uint8).notice: setFrozen sets the frozen status of an account to any of the values documented in                   FreezeStatusEnum.

setFundingClampPct(uint256,uint256).notice: setFundingClampPct sets the magnitude percentage that the funding rate clamps to if it                            is exceeded. This applies to both negative funding rate percentage                            or positive funding rate percentage.                            For example if this is set to a value corresponding to 4%, then                            funding rates of 5% and -6% would be clamped to 4% and -4%,                            respectively.

setFundingSum(uint256,int256,uint32,bool.notice: setFundingSum sets the funding sum for the specified perpetual contract. See dev                       comments below for applicable conditions.

setIgnOracle(uint256,bool).notice: CAREFUL: Configures the perpetual contract to ignore Oracle checks for:                    1. Setting the Mark price.                    2. Setting the Funding rate (an Funding Event Price is provided for this and                    ordinarily checked against the Oracle price).                    3. Unpausing the perpetual contract the first time (ordinarily this requires                       an oracle to be configured).                   Attempting to update the Oracle price will be ignored with event emitted.

setInitialMarginFraction(uint256,uint256.notice: setInitialMarginFraction sets the Initial Margin Fraction (IMF), synonymous with the                                  maximum initial leverage of a position, for the specified                                  perpetual contract.

setLastForwardedDescId(uint256,uint256).notice: setLastForwardedDescId allows an administrator to reset the lastForwardedDescId for an account.

setLastForwardedDescIdAsOwner(uint256,ui.notice: setLastForwardedDescIdAsOwner allows the owner to reset the lastForwardedDescId for an         account.

setLastTriggeredDescId(uint256,uint256).notice: setLastTriggeredDescId allows an administrator to set the lastTriggeredDescId for an account.

setLinkDsVerifier(address).notice: Sets the Chainlink Datastreams Verifier Proxy address for the entire exchange.

setLiquidationBuyer(address,bool).notice: setLiquidationBuyer This function controls the ability of an existing account to                             perform purchase liquidations, referred to as a buy to liquidate                             operation. Buy to liquidate differs from permissioned liquidation                             to the order book by allowing users or permissioned users                             (depending upon configuration), to purchase a liquidatable position                             at the mark price, if it meets the buy to liquidate price                             criteria. The purchased liquidation's proceeds can be configurably                             directed to the position purchaser to incentivize the purchase                             risk. The buy to liquidate price criteria is configurable to a                             price between a positions liquidation price and bankruptcy price;                             this permits the ability to prioritize liquidations to the order                             book if desired.

setLiquidationParams(uint256,uint256,uin.notice: setLiquidationParams sets the split for the proceeds of a liquidation, directing                              configurable portions of the funds to the insurance fund, the                              original position holder and to the protocol (liquidator).

setMaintenanceMarginFraction(uint256,uin.notice: setMaintenanceMarginFraction sets the Maintenance Margin Fraction (MMF). This is the                                      used to calculate the margin (value) that a position must                                      maintain in order to avoid liquidation by the system.

setMakerFee(uint256,uint256).notice: setMakerFee sets the maker fee, the fee applicable to orders that have posted to the                     book and are then matched to open a position.                     IMPORTANT: The maker fee only applies when opening a position--either a new                     position or increasing an existing position. It does NOT apply to reducing                     a position.

setMarginTol(uint256,uint256,uint256).notice: Sets the tolerance that the borrow margin check may deviate from the computed BMR when         decreasing collateral. The tolerance is expressed as tolerance/10^decimals.

setMaxOpenInterest(uint256,uint256).notice: setMaxOpenInterest CAREFUL! This sets the maximum open interest of the perpetual                            contract. The effect is not a hard cap but rather determines the                            maximum initial leverage of a position, which can range from                            [1/100, 100.0], depending on the perpetual contract's initial                            setting and how far open interest has progressed towards the maximum                            value specified here (and the unity and over collateral descent                            thresholds).                            See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more information.

setMinAccountOpenAmount(uint256).notice: setMinAccountOpenAmount sets the minimum amount that must be transferred into an                                 account when it is created. Transferring less than the minimum                                 amount will result in the account creation operation reverting.

setMinPost(uint256).notice: setMinPost sets the minimum amount for an order to post to the book. See dev notes                    below about behavior of this function for different order and position                    combinations.

setMinSettle(uint256).notice: setMinSettle sets the minimum amount for an order to settle on the book. See dev notes                      below about behavior of this function for different order and position                      combinations.

setMinWithdrawLimit(uint256).notice: setMinWithdrawLimit sets the limit minimum that can be withdrawn per rate limit                             interval. If the computed limit for an interval is less than                             this value, then this value supercedes the computed limit and is                             used to compute the withdrawal amount per block for the rate                             limit interval.                             Changes to this value take effect in the next rate limit                             interval if there is currently one ongoing.

setOverCollatDescentThreshold(uint256,ui.notice: setOverCollatDescentThreshold CAREFUL! This sets the threshold at which the Initial                                       Margin Fraction (IMF) of the perpetual contract begins                                       its descent to the over collateral minimum IMF, 1/100th.                                       The threshold applies to the perpetual's open interest as                                       a fraction of the perpetual's maximum open interest.                                       See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more information.

setPermissionedCancelParams(uint256,uint.notice: setPermissionedCancelParams sets the parameters that determine if permissioned                                     cancellation criteria are applicable, allowing                                     adminCancelOrders to be applied to orders distant from the                                     mid-price that might be performing denial of service attacks                                     on the order book. See documentation of the following                                     functions for more information:                                       * Admin::adminCancelOrders                                       * OrderBookLib::meetsOrderBookCapacityCancelCriteria

setPerpLinkDsFeedId(uint256,bytes32).notice: Configures a perpetual contract's Chainlink Datastream feed id. Requires that the         perpetual contract is paused and that the Chainlink Datastream Verifier Proxy has been         set. Reverts otherwise.

setPositionAdministrator(address,bool).notice: setPositionAdministrator CAREFUL! This function allows an address to be permitted to                                  the role of position administrator. A position administrator can do                                  important, financially impactful updates to a perpetual                                  contract including liquidation, auto-deleveraging, and closing                                  a frozen account's positions to the order book..                                  This role is not suitable for a multi-sig because the                                  frequency of operations and number of operations is too high.                                  Protection against this role being co-opted comes in the form                                  of the price oracle guarding price changes to be within a                                  certain tolerance, closing to the order book, and age as well                                  as a last resort, the owner called halt function which blocks                                  addresses with this role from acting on the exchange.                                  The number of position administrators is not limited as this                                  role will likely operate with both failover and geographic                                  redundancy.

setPriceAdministrator(address,bool).notice: setPriceAdministrator CAREFUL! This function allows an address to be permitted to the                               role of price administrator. A price administrator can do                               important, financially impactful updates to a perpetual contract                               including setting the mark price and funding rate for the                               perpetual contract.                               This role is not suitable for a multi-sig because the frequency                               of operations and number of operations is too high. Protection                               against this role being co-opted comes in the form of the price                               oracle guarding price changes to be within a certain tolerance                               and age as well as a last resort, the owner called halt function                               which blocks addresses with this role from acting on the                               exchange.                               The number of price administrators is not limited as this role                               will likely operate with both failover and geographic redundancy.

setPriceTolPer100K(uint256,uint256).notice: Sets the tolerance a price may deviate from the spot oracle price. Applicable in two         scenarios:           1. The setting of the mark price. The mark price must be within the specified              tolerance of the oracle price.           2. The setting of a funding event. The specified funding price must be within the              specified tolerance of the oracle price.

setPriceTolPer100KByOwner(uint256,uint25.notice: Sets the tolerance a price may deviate from the spot oracle price. Applicable in two         scenarios:           1. The setting of the mark price. The mark price must be within the specified              tolerance of the oracle price.           2. The setting of a funding event. The specified funding price must be within the              specified tolerance of the oracle price.

setRecycleFee(uint256).notice: setRecycleFee sets the order recycling fee, which applies to all orders exchange wide.                       The recycling fee is remitted by an account posting an order to a                       perpetual's order book, which is then refunded when the order fills or is                       cancelled.                       Exceptions to the refunding include:                         a. When an order is expired.                         b. When an order cannot be filled due to failed risk analysis                            (collateralization).                         c. When an order meets certain permissioned cancellation criteria. (See                            documentation for Admin::adminCancelOrders).                       In these cases, the recycling fee is remitted to the order taker or                       administrator role (when the administrator role is order forwarding or                       performing permissioned adminCancelOrders calls).

setTakerFee(uint256,uint256).notice: setTakerFee sets the taker fee, the fee applicable to orders that execute immediately,                     matching positions on the order book, to open a position.                     IMPORTANT: The taker fee only applies when opening a position--either a new                     position or increasing an existing position. It does NOT apply to reducing                     a position.

setThousandthsTvlWRLS(uint256).notice: setThousandthsTvlWRLS sets the thousandths of Total Value Locked (TVL) in the protocol                               that can be withdrawn per withdraw rate limit period in the                               Withdrawal Rate Limit System (WRLS).                               The withdraw rate limit period is block based and is                               approximately an hour if Monad block consensus is averaging 0.42                               seconds.

setToleranceAdministrator(address,bool).notice: setToleranceAdministrator CAREFUL! This function allows an address to be permitted to                                   the role of tolerance administrator. A tolerance administrator can                                   change the allowable tolerance that a mark price update must                                   meet, relative to the oracle price. This has significant                                   impact on the perpetual financially in the event that one or                                   more price administrator keys are compromised. The role is                                   separated out to allow more rapid changes to the tolerance                                   than would be possible if tolerances could only be set by the                                   owner multi-sig.                                   For example, the tolerance service could analyze prices and                                   ensure that the tolerance is set dynamically to minimize                                   damage in the event of a price administrator key compromise                                   based on heuristic data.                                   This role is unsuitable for a multi-sig account because the                                   number and frequency of operations is too high and the                                   response time of a multi-sig is too slow. Protection against                                   key(s) assigned to this role being compromised comes                                   from the owner-callable exchange halt function. When the                                   exchange is halted, the addresses associated with the                                   ToleranceAdministrator role are blocked from acting on the                                   exchange.                                   The number of tolerance administrators is not limited as this                                   role will likely operate with both failover and geographic                                   redundancy.

setUnityDescentThreshold(uint256,uint256.notice: setUnityDescentThreshold CAREFUL! This sets the threshold at which the Initial Margin                                  Fraction (IMF) of the perpetual contract begins its descent to                                  unity. The threshold applies to the perpetual's open interest                                  as a fraction of the perpetual's maximum open interest.                                  See CalculationsLib::getCurrentIMF for more information.

setWhitelistingEnabled(bool).notice: Enables or disables the whitelist requirement for account creation.

setWithdrawBypass(address,bool).notice: Allows the owner to designate addresses that bypass the withdraw rate limit.

triggerUnwindContract(uint256).notice: Emits an optional event indicating that contract unwinding can begin. Requires that the         contract is paused and the unwind process has been initialized.         This call is optional, enabling communication through the blockchain to backend         services with the PositionAdministrator role to commence the unwind process.         Communication in this way isolates these services from other forms of communication         which could increase attack surface area.

unwindContract(uint256,uint256,bool).notice: Unwinds a perpetual contract for restart or delisting by paying out all         remaining positive valued positions from the perpetual contract's position and         insurance /balance.         IMPORTANT - CAREFUL: See documentation of Owner::unwindContractByOwner for details                              about the unwind process.

unwindContractByOwner(uint256,uint256,bo.notice: Unwinds a perpetual contract for restart or delisting by paying out all         remaining positive valued positions from the perpetual contract's position and         insurance balance. See dev note on the unwind process below.

updateMarkPricePNS(uint256,uint32).notice: updateMarkPricePNS updates the mark price of the specified perpetual contract. See                            dev comments below for applicable conditions.

updateMarkPricePNSByOwner(uint256,uint32.notice: Updates the mark price of the specified perpetual contract. See dev comments below for         applicable conditions.

updateOraclePrice(uint256,bytes).notice: Attempts to update the specified perpetual contract's oracle price with a signed,         unverified, Chainlink Datastreams V3 price report.         IMPORTANT: This will emit OracleDisabled event and exit if the perpetual is configured                    to ignore oracle prices (see Perpetual::ignOracle and                    Owner::setIgnOracle).

withdrawCollateral(uint256).notice: withdrawCollateral allows an existing exchange account, determined by the address in                            msg.sender, to withdraw a specified amount of collateral tokens from                            their available collateral.

withdrawFromProtocol(uint256).notice: withdrawFromProtocol allows the owner account to withdraw collateral tokens from the                              protocol balance to an external wallet.

xferAcctToProtocol(uint256).notice: xferAcctToProtocol transfers funds from the user account, if it exists, corresponding                            to the address in msg.sender, to the protocol balance.

xferPerpInsToProtocol(uint256,uint256).notice: xferPerpInsToProtocol transfers funds from a specified perpetual contract's insurance                               fund balance to the protocol balance.

xferProtocolToAcct(uint256,uint256).notice: xferProtocolToPerp transfers funds from the protocol balance to a specified account's                            collateral balance.

xferProtocolToPerp(uint256,uint256,bool).notice: xferProtocolToPerp transfers funds from the protocol balance to a specified perpetual                            contract's position balance or insurance balance.

xferProtocolToRecycleBal(uint256).notice: xferProtocolToPerp transfers funds from the protocol balance to the protocol wide order                            recycling fee balance.
